cs.CR, cs.DS, cs.IT, cs.CC, cs.DC

This paper deals with the topic of Oblivious RAM (ORAM), which is a cryptographic primitive used for protecting the privacy of data access patterns. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). The paper also involves the study of access graphs induced by the memory access pattern of an ORAM computation, which is related to data structures and algorithms. Hence, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is also a likely category. The paper also involves information theory and communication complexity, which are related to cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity). Finally, the paper involves lower bounds, which are related to cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing).
